<DOC><DOCNO> AP880419-0105 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1117EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Nail-GunSuicide 2ndLd-Writethru a05</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Nail-Gun Suicide, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0564,0201</SECOND><HEAD>Man Stabs Estranged Wife, Kills Self With Nail Gun</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with woman's condition</NOTE><DATELINE>MERRIMACK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A 33-year-old man stabbed his estrangedwife with a hunting knife early today, then killed himself with ashot to the head from a high-powered nail gun, police said.   Patricia Lecam, 28, survived and fled through her bedroom windowto a neighbor's house with her three young children, police said.She was in fair condition at a hospital this morning, officialssaid.   Deputy Chief William Mulligan said police heard what soundedlike a single gunshot when they arrived at the home in response toa report of a burglary in progress at 1:08 a.m.   A search turned up William Lecam's body lying in the woods about150 yards behind the house, Mulligan said. He had shot himself inthe head with a nail gun, Mulligan said.   Nail guns are used in construction to save time. Most are drivenby compressed air fed through hoses, but Mulligan said this oneapparently used cartridges containing a small explosive charge.   Lecam had been arrested in February on charges of assaulting hiswife, Mulligan said.</TEXT></DOC>